European Defence and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, Nazi occupation.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the middle of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests and confrontations in Europe for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined together, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political unit, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could ever be two Europes  one democratic, stable, prosperous and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous and isolated  is a mistake.
It is as if one part of a room could be heated while the other part remained cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event elicits an echo across Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to incorporate the new post-communist democracies – which is in Europe's interest –, a series of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must promote community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a vibrant society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a shared continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more they are connected to each other, the better prepared the new democracies will be for membership in the EU and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer diverse solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economic it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that the central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy, which sacrificed European solidarity and led to the Munich capitulation.
This experience is still a strong call for vigilance.
One must confront the evil as soon as it appears, but it is not enough for only governments to act.
For government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make quick decisions and to implement communal decisions rapidly – reforms that were deemed necessary by recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the interests of European security, require interventions beyond the EU's borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action is, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations in which the UN mandate may not come, even though an intervention is in the interest of many people, of all of Europe, indeed of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared for it, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
There is still much more needed in the field of preventive security, but it is also necessary for this security to reflect the values of Europe's expanded civil society.
Tens of thousands of human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was timid.
These failures were the result of diverse individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot forever remain dependent on the US, especially regarding European problems.
It must be able to agree on its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves incapable of agreeing on means and ways to protect human rights, not only on its own territory, but also in areas that may one day join it.
Such an EU expansion is only feasible if it proceeds hand in hand with a determined reform of EU institutions.
I am confident that the government conference on institutional reform will put forward practical proposals for advancing the Union.
But I see this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting commitment to accelerate and make EU decision-making more transparent.
An issue related to institutional reform is how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be outvoted by the larger ones, while still adequately taking into account the size of each country.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would not be elected directly, but would be chosen by the parliaments of the member states from their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU – that is, the current Parliament – would therefore reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber would, with an equal number of representatives for each country, increase equality.
These changes will eventually require that the EU have a clear, understandable constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution would need two parts.
Part one would define the rights and responsibilities of both European citizens and states, as well as the underlying values and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships with each other.
Such a fundamental law would not automatically transform the current Union into the federal superstate feared by Euroskeptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to understand what the EU stands for, to better comprehend it, to see the significance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, to identify with it.
